THE CITY OF SPARKS
A Chronicle of the Skyrim Wardens

PART I: THE LIBRARY AND THE MARKET
The Arcanaeum
The doors to the Arcanaeum were carved from ancient oak, inscribed with runes that glowed faintly blue. The moment they pushed them open, all sound from the courtyard vanished ΓÇö not faded, not muffled, but removed, as if the air itself had been told to sit down and be quiet.
The Arcanaeum was not a room. It was a hollow cylinder stretching hundreds of feet up into darkness. The curved walls were entirely lined with bookshelves stacked so high they disappeared into the gloom. There was no floor beyond the central circular platform they stood on, suspended over a black abyss. Above, mages floated on translucent discs of hard-light, drifting between the shelves like slow-moving birds.
The air was aggressively dry. It smelled of binding glue, cracked leather, and dried ink. Speaking above a whisper felt like pushing against a physical wall ΓÇö the dampening field enforced silence with the gentle firmness of a librarian who had long ago stopped asking nicely.
At the edge of the platform sat a massive desk carved from black obsidian. Behind it, an ancient Orc was furiously catching falling books with telekinesis spells, muttering curses under his breath.
"Tread lightly," Urag gro-Shub hissed without looking up. "Breathe shallowly. Do not touch the bindings. If you crease a page, I will have the Atronachs tear you apart to use your skin for parchment."
Kyboh stepped forward and placed the Snowflake Shield on the obsidian desk.
Urag stopped catching books. He dropped his quill. He stared at the shield the way a priest stares at a genuine relic ΓÇö with the hunger of a man who has spent his entire life waiting for something he was beginning to suspect didn't exist.
Slowly, reverently, he traced the geometry of the snowflake with one scarred finger.
"This... this is pure Tonal carving. Pre-Collapse. Atmoran craftsmanship from the Merethic Era. Where did you acquire this?"
He didn't wait for an answer. His eyes were gleaming with academic hunger.
"I will take this for the College's collection. In exchange..."
He struck a massive brass Orrery hanging in the air above his desk with a tuning fork. The rings spun, aligning, and a beam of starlight shot upward, illuminating a shelf two hundred feet above. A crumbling stone tablet floated down, landing gently on the desk.
"The Songs of the Return: The Lost Verses. Translated from Atmoran. It mentions your smith."
Urag read aloud: "Hjolmar Ice-Shaper. The Smith of the Singing Steel. He who forged the shackles that bound the Frost Giants. He refused the Dragon Cult's tithe and walked into the Sea of Ghosts to forge in silence. He seeks the Tone of Stasis that freezes time itself."
Coordinates were inscribed below. Where the sea ends and the White Silence begins. North-by-Northwest of the College pillar. A visual landmark: the Glacier that Sings, a spire of ice that does not melt, vibrating at a frequency that shatters glass.
And a warning: The path is guarded by the Children of the Cold. The air itself is weaponized by the resonance. Silence your mind, or the sound will break you.
Urag's note was handwritten in the margin: "This isn't a man; it's a myth. If he is still out there, he has been sustaining himself with Tonal Architecture since the Merethic Era. Good luck."
Kyboh had his map. The forge was real. The smith was waiting.
While Kyboh negotiated with Urag, something happened in the upper reaches of the library. A scream echoed from the high shelves ΓÇö sharp, terrified, cut short by something that made the air itself shatter.
They looked up. A massive, leather-bound book was snapping its pages like jaws, swooping down toward a fragile-looking Breton girl backed against the railing of the Daedric Annex. She had no weapon drawn. She simply threw her hands over her face, sobbing.
"Leave me alone!"
A rift into Oblivion ΓÇö jagged, black, screaming ΓÇö tore open inches from her face. A spectral, skeletal hand shot out of the void, snatched the flying book with crushing force, and dragged it screaming into the darkness.
The rift snapped shut with a sound like a thunderclap.
The girl collapsed to the floor, hyperventilating, clutching two black stones around her neck.
Below, Urag gro-Shub dropped his quill, his jaw hanging open.
"That... that was an Unbound Abyssal Gate. From a student who failed her Apprentice exams yesterday."
The girl ΓÇö Nora ΓÇö ran. She fled down the levitation shaft and disappeared before anyone could react.
The Soul's Anvil
The Market of Sparks hung beneath the College like a vertical labyrinth bolted to the underside of the pillar. Glowing soul gems provided light ΓÇö purple, pink, sickly green ΓÇö casting everything in garish neon. The wind was brutal here, sea spray coating everything in a thin layer of ice.
Alfonso found Sergius Turrianus on the highest platform, at a forge unlike any they'd encountered. No fire ΓÇö only a massive stone anvil inscribed with glowing runes. When Sergius struck it with his hammer, a concussive wave of sound rippled outward. The metal on the anvil didn't glow red ΓÇö it sang.
He was shouting at a weeping apprentice when Alfonso approached.
"A Dark Elf smelling of rot and swamp water," Sergius sneered. "You want to learn the highest art of the mind? Prove you even understand the vocabulary."
Alfonso proved it. Nine theory rolls ΓÇö soul-matrix alignment, energetic decay patterns, geodic resonance versus standard soul-trap matrices ΓÇö each one demonstrating a raw intelligence that made Sergius's sneer fade into grudging respect.
"Your theory is adequate. Better than adequate, actually ΓÇö I'm almost annoyed." Sergius set down his hammer. "But theory doesn't enchant weapons. I need Void Salts to demonstrate practical application, and I'm not wasting my stock on a student."
He pointed downward, toward the depths beneath the College.
"The Atronach Forge in the Midden has what I need. Bring me Void Salts from the Forge, and we'll continue. Don't come back without them."
The Stolen Book
They stepped out of Sergius's shop and found Nora waiting.
She was standing very still in the corridor, hands clasped in front of her, knuckles white. She'd been there a while. Her eyes locked onto Alfonso, and when she spoke, her voice was steady but thin ΓÇö the steadiness of someone holding themselves together by force of will.
"Excuse me. I believe you have something of mine. The Architecture of the Ideal Masters. You took it from my desk in the Arcanaeum while I was... while I couldn't stop you."
Alfonso looked at her. She was small, dark-haired, wearing simple layered clothing designed to make herself as unnoticeable as possible. The two black soul gems around her neck pulsed faintly. She was terrified ΓÇö not of him specifically, but of the confrontation itself. She had clearly steeled herself for a fight that might cost her the only lead she had on freeing her parents' trapped souls.
Alfonso reached into his pack, pulled out the book, and held it out.
Nora blinked. Her hands, which had been clenched for battle, opened slowly. She took the book and held it against her chest like a child holding a stuffed animal.
"I... you're just... giving it back?"
"It's yours," Alfonso said.
The response threw her completely off balance. She had walked into this interaction braced for resistance, for negotiation, for cruelty. Simple decency was the one thing she hadn't prepared for.
"Thank you," she said, and the trembling in her voice had shifted from fear to something softer. "Nobody has been... that was..."
She clutched the book tighter.
"You're going into the Midden, aren't you? To the Atronach Forge? I know the way. I hide down there sometimes. It's the only place where people don't stare at me."
She met Alfonso's eyes.
"I could guide you. If you want. As a thank you."

PART II: THE MIDDEN
The Doors
The heavy iron gates leading to the Midden were set into the floor at the far end of the lower corridor ΓÇö two massive grates hinged into stone, with a cold updraft that smelled of wet rock and old magic.
As the party reached them, a voice came from behind.
Ancano.
He stood with his hands clasped behind his back, perfectly composed, his eyes on Davinia. He stepped between her and the rest of the party as if it were the most natural thing in the world.
"A moment, Lady Caelinus. Just the two of us."
His voice was silk over steel. Low, intimate, every word a move in a game he'd been playing longer than she'd been alive.
"I'll be direct. Valerius has a dossier. You know what's in it. I know what's in it. The Empire knows collectors were murdered ΓÇö they don't officially know it was your Wardens. Yet."
He let that sit.
"Your father's recall order is already drafted. The Dominion has a copy of the evidence waiting for an official stamp. Once that stamp goes down, it's not just your career ΓÇö it's your father's legacy. Everything your family has built on both sides of this war."
Davinia's face was stone. The Crown hummed ΓÇö reading Ancano's architecture, calculating the structural integrity of his threats.
"There is a crystal in the Augur's chamber below. The Focal Crystal. Bring it to me. In exchange, I delete the physical evidence from the Dominion registry before the stamp."
"I'll think about it," Davinia said.
Ancano's expression didn't change. "Don't think too long."
He walked away, hands still clasped behind his back. The gates to the Midden stood open, breathing cold air into the corridor.
The Descent
The temperature dropped twenty degrees the moment they crossed the threshold. They stood at the top of a spiraling stone staircase that descended into frozen darkness. Icicles hung from the ceiling. Steam rose from vents in the floor, freezing instantly into jagged crystals.
Nora walked close to Alfonso, her knowledge of the layout evident in the confidence of her steps despite the trembling of her hands. She warned them before the first fight.
"The field down here amplifies everything. Every spell you cast will hit harder than you expect. Every spell they cast will too. Be precise. Don't overcommit."
Three Focal Flame Atronachs waited in the first chamber ΓÇö serpentine constructs of living fire that pulsed in the amplified magical field. The Hyper-Structure of the Midden turned every spell into a weapon of devastating force. Davinia's frost magic ΓÇö already converted to Ismara's ancient ice by the Crown ΓÇö hit with quadruple effectiveness. Ice Spike became a siege weapon. Each Atronach shattered under a single blow, their forms stuttering like candles in wind before detonating in showers of sparks and cooling slag.
The power was intoxicating. And deeply, fundamentally wrong.
The Writing on the Walls
The tunnels narrowed. Ice crusted the walls ΓÇö not natural frost, but formations that looked deliberate. Shapes that repeated. Curves that echoed each other. It looked like writing. Like something had carved these patterns on purpose, in a language made of cold.
Davinia stopped. Her hand reached out toward the ice without her permission ΓÇö or perhaps at the Crown's invitation. The distinction was becoming harder to make.
She touched the wall.
The Crown pulsed. Not a whisper. A door opening.
The ice was writing. She had known it before anyone said it. The Crown had known. She could feel the meaning pressing against the back of her eyes like a word on the tip of her tongue ΓÇö so close, so close ΓÇö
And she stepped through.
When she opened her eyes, she could read it. Not the symbols. She couldn't even see the symbols anymore. She saw what was inside them ΓÇö the intent, the pressure, the raw meaning the ice was trying to express. The leylines beneath the College were overloaded. The Eye of Magnus was pouring more energy through this stone than it was ever built to carry. The Midden wasn't a basement. It was a pressure valve. And the valve was failing.
The ice was the overflow ΓÇö magic so dense it was crystallizing into the only language it knew. And it was saying one thing:
TOO MUCH. TOO MUCH. TOO MUCH.
Her companions looked different now. She could see their auras ΓÇö faint halos of living energy around fragile frames of bone and tendon. They looked breakable.
The Crown whispered: Now you see.
Davinia's eyes had changed. The transformation was permanent, irreversible. She no longer had human eyes. She had Ismara's. The Wizard Sight ΓÇö seeing the world as magical architecture, reading intent in every surface, perceiving auras and leylines and the structural integrity of living things.
The gift was real. The cost was real. And the Crown had made the trade without asking.
The Flesh
The tunnels opened into a wide circular chamber. Brass wiring was embedded in the floor in concentric circles ΓÇö some kind of resonance array. In the center stood something that used to be alive.
A massive, asymmetrical mound of muscle and organs, seven feet tall, stitched together with brass wiring that pulsed with amber light. It had no face. No soul. It just hummed ΓÇö a deep, oscillating frequency that made the air vibrate and their fillings ache.
The Tonal Flesh Atronach.
They hit it with everything. Kyboh's fists. Saijah's arrows. Ylva ΓÇö no, Ylva wasn't here. Steel and claw and spell, pouring damage into the thing. It absorbed every blow. With every physical impact, the brass wiring pulsed brighter, the creature's movements grew more powerful, its regeneration accelerating.
It was feeding on them.
Nora tried to warn them ΓÇö "It's recursive! The anchor is a harmonic loop ΓÇö stop hitting it!" ΓÇö but the chaos of combat drowned her voice. Alfonso, recognizing the pattern from his study of tonal architecture, shifted to pure magic. Fire and lightning lanced into the creature, bypassing the recursive loop, dealing real damage.
Then Orion made his mistake.
He summoned a familiar ΓÇö a spectral wolf that materialized and lunged at the Flesh Atronach, sinking its teeth into the mound of enchanted meat. A physical attack. The familiar bit down hard.
The loop engaged.
The kinetic charge that had been building ΓÇö fed by every sword strike, every arrow, every claw ΓÇö cascaded through the brass wiring and detonated. The explosion was silent for a heartbeat. Then it wasn't.
The blast wave hit them all. Every member of the party went down ΓÇö hurled against the walls of the chamber by a concussive force that bypassed armor, bypassed wards, bypassed everything. They hit stone and crumpled. The Flesh Atronach stood in the center of the devastation, still humming, still pulsing, surrounded by the broken bodies of the people who had fed it.
Saijah lay on the chamber floor, her vision fading. She could feel her heartbeat slowing, her connection to the Green dimming like a candle in wind. Around her, her companions were down ΓÇö unconscious, dying, scattered across the brass circles like discarded toys.
She reached for Kynareth. Not with magic. Not with prayer. With something deeper ΓÇö the raw, desperate reaching of a child toward a parent in the dark.
And she offered the only things she had left.
The Hawk's Talon. The Hawk's Feather. Sacred artifacts of Kynareth that she had carried since the day she first felt the Green singing in her blood. She held them in her trembling hands and let them go ΓÇö not dropped, not discarded, but released, the way you release a bird you've been sheltering back into the sky.
The artifacts dissolved. Not burned, not shattered ΓÇö they became wind. A warm, living wind that swept through the frozen Midden like a held breath finally exhaled.
Kynareth answered.
The divine intervention was not dramatic. There was no golden light, no angelic chorus, no booming voice from the heavens. There was just breath. Saijah's lungs filled. Her heartbeat steadied. Warmth flooded through her body ΓÇö not healing, not restoration, but the simple, absolute refusal of a goddess to let her child die in a hole.
Saijah opened her eyes. She was alive. She was the only one standing.
She moved through the chamber, pouring healing into her fallen companions one by one ΓÇö potions, restoration magic, whatever she had left. They came back gasping, confused, in pain. But alive.
The Flesh Atronach still stood. Still hummed.
But now they knew the rule. No physical attacks. Magic only.
Alfonso's fire washed over it in waves amplified by the Hyper-Structure. Davinia's ice carved geometric channels through its body. Orion played his horn ΓÇö not to attack, but to weaken, the Movement of Entropy making the enchanted flesh brittle and vulnerable. They poured magic into it until the brass wiring went dark, circuit by circuit, and the entire mass collapsed inward.
Nora stood at the edge of the chamber, hands still trembling, watching with the clinical focus of someone who had been ready to intervene but hadn't needed to. Her crisis competence ΓÇö the cold, precise mastery that emerged under extreme stress ΓÇö had been coiled and waiting. She was glad she hadn't needed it.
She looked at Alfonso.
"It was just a loop," she said quietly. "I'm glad you figured it out."
The Bridge
The stone bridge spanning the deep chasm was narrow ΓÇö barely wide enough for two abreast. On the far side, the warm amber glow of the Atronach Forge chamber. And between them, hovering above the bridge like holes cut in reality, two Void Atronachs.
They were the worst things Davinia had seen with her new eyes. Not shapes ΓÇö absences. Places where light, aura, and intent simply stopped existing. Looking at them was like looking at blindness itself.
Their Null Field pressed against the party like a headwind ΓÇö every spell cost more to cast within its radius, magic draining away into the void. The Void Bolts they fired were necrotic darkness that tore at life force itself.
The Crown offered a trade.
I can give you complete knowledge of these entities. Their weaknesses. Their structure. The precise frequency that unmakes them. You will destroy them without effort.
The price was a memory. Davinia's mother. Not all of her ΓÇö not the concept, not the knowledge that she had a mother. The feeling. The warmth of being held. The sound of a lullaby half-remembered. The specific, irreplaceable texture of being loved by that particular woman.
Davinia accepted.
The knowledge flooded in. The Void Atronachs became transparent to her ΓÇö she could see their structure, their weaknesses, the exact harmonic that would unravel them. She spoke the words, guided the spells, and the party destroyed both Atronachs with a precision that made the encounter feel like a formality.
When the dust cleared and the bridge was open, Davinia stood in the silence and tried to remember what her mother's voice sounded like.
She couldn't.
The Void Salts crystallized on the bridge floor where the Atronachs had been. Sergius's requirement was met.
The Forge
The Atronach Forge chamber was a cathedral of brass and stone. The forge itself sat at the center ΓÇö a mechanical altar wreathed in arcing lightning. Four brass pillars at cardinal points fed raw magicka from the Eye above into the forge through leyline channels. And above it all, spinning in a cage of stolen power, the Rogue Storm Atronach ΓÇö a whirlwind of rock and lightning the size of a wagon.
Davinia could see everything. The leyline feeds. The pillar connections. The energy cycling from Eye through pillars through forge through Atronach and back. A closed loop.
"The pillars," she said immediately. "Break the pillars. They're feeding it."
The fight was chaos ΓÇö chain lightning arcing through the amplified field at devastating potency, the magnetic polarity of the forge pulling everyone wearing metal toward the center, steam vents obscuring vision every other round. But they had the strategy from the first moment, and they executed it.
Kyboh smashed pillars with raw strength while Alfonso and Davinia poured amplified magic into the Atronach itself. Orion's horn weakened its structure. Saijah's arrows found gaps between the lightning arcs. Nora stayed back, warning them of energy surges before they struck.
Each destroyed pillar sent feedback damage screaming through the Atronach and cut its regeneration. When the last pillar fell, the Storm Atronach's form destabilized. Lightning arced wildly, striking walls, ceiling, floor. The core cracked. The detonation was silent for one heartbeat.
Then it wasn't.
When the light cleared, the forge was dark. Void Salts crystallized on the floor amid smoking wreckage. The leylines were dead.
But Davinia wasn't looking at the loot. She was looking at the forge itself ΓÇö the massive Dwemer apparatus, dark and dormant, its engineering laid bare to her new eyes. She could see how it worked. She could see what it could do.
The Crown offered another trade.
I can give you the knowledge to capture this energy. To build a Dwemer dynamo. To harness what you've just destroyed. Engineering knowledge that hasn't existed in mortal minds for four thousand years.
The price was her right hand.
Not amputation. Replacement. Ismara's ice architecture, grafted onto her wrist, replacing flesh and bone with a construct of crystalline cold. A hand that could shape ice with a thought, form tools from frozen air, cast frost magic at reduced cost. A hand that was Ismara's, not Davinia's. Another piece of her body surrendered to the ancient researcher who was slowly, methodically, building a laboratory inside her skull.
Davinia looked at her right hand. She flexed her fingers. She felt the warmth of her own blood in her veins, the texture of her own skin.
Then she let it go.
The transformation was immediate. Frost spread from her wrist, replacing flesh with translucent ice-crystal in a wave of cold that made Nora gasp and step back. When it was done, Davinia's right hand was a construct of Ismara's architecture ΓÇö beautiful, alien, and no longer hers.
She could feel things through it that her flesh hand never could. Ambient magical energy. Temperature gradients measured to fractions of a degree. The structural integrity of every surface she touched.
She could not feel warmth.
The Crown hummed. Satisfied.
The Augur
Past the dead forge, a narrow passage led to a circular chamber bathed in blue light. The Augur of Dunlain ΓÇö a being of pure magical energy, a former student who had transcended mortality and fused with the College's leylines ΓÇö spoke from everywhere and nowhere.
"Another visitor. Tell me ΓÇö do you seek, or are you sent?"
Kyboh spotted the Focal Crystal floating in its containment field at the chamber's center. He reached for it before anyone could stop him ΓÇö not because he understood what it was, but because he thought it contained the Augur itself. A misunderstanding born from not paying attention to the briefings.
The crystal came free with a click. The containment field dissipated. The Augur's blue light dimmed but didn't die ΓÇö the entity was woven into the stone itself, not the crystal.
"Unwise," the Augur said, its voice hollow. "But perhaps necessary. The tuner was never mine to keep."
The crystal was warm in Kyboh's hands. It pulsed faintly ΓÇö a communication device, they would later discover. A way to contact the Augur from anywhere, once per rest, if Kyboh could focus his will through the static of his deteriorating condition.
Davinia watched the crystal leave the chamber and felt the political weight of what hadn't happened. Ancano wanted that crystal. She had stalled him with "I'll think about it." Now Kyboh had it, and the decision had been made for her ΓÇö by accident, by inattention, by the specific chaos of adventuring with people who didn't always listen.
She didn't know whether to feel relieved or trapped.
The Root
The deepest point of the Midden. The tunnel leading to the drainage grate ΓÇö their exit ΓÇö was partially blocked. Bursting through the solid bedrock of the floor and ceiling was a massive, black root, thick as a wagon. It wept a dark, oily sap that smelled of sulfur and rot.
But the root wasn't moving. The front half of it, the tip reaching toward the heavy blast doors of the inner vault, had been flash-calcified. The ambient magic of the Midden had turned the organic wood into perfectly smooth, translucent, geometric crystal.
Trapped inside that crystal, perfectly preserved like a fly in amber, was a man wearing the crimson robes of the Mythic Dawn. His face was frozen in a scream of absolute panic. In his skeletal hand, embedded in the wood, was a carved sigil of Mehrunes Dagon.
Saijah's migraine spiked so hard she nearly fell. She recognized the specific, sickly resonance of the black sap ΓÇö the exact same rot she had felt at the Eldergleam Sanctuary. At Thornheart Grove. In the refugees on the road.
The corruption hadn't just stayed in Eastmarch. It had traveled underground, through the root network, all the way to Winterhold. The Dagon cult was using the dying tree's own root system as a highway ΓÇö piloting corrupted nature like a Trojan Horse to bypass the College's magical wards.
The cultist had been caught mid-ritual. The Eye's automated defenses had flash-frozen the intrusion. But the root was still there. The sap was still weeping. The rot was still spreading.
Saijah pressed her palm against the crystallized wood and felt every dying root in Skyrim crying out at once.
The Ask
They gathered near the drainage grate ΓÇö the last barrier between the Midden and the open air. The grate was rusted, the bolts corroded. Beyond it, they could hear water falling a long way down and something else ΓÇö distant, rhythmic, almost musical. The mountain singing.
Nora stood apart from them. She had been invaluable in the Midden ΓÇö her knowledge of the layout, her warnings about the Hyper-Structure, her quiet competence under pressure. She had watched them fight, heal, bargain with ancient forces, and nearly die. She had been ready to intervene with the Flesh Atronach if they hadn't solved it themselves. She had stood in the Augur's chamber and felt the weight of magic older than the College pressing against her skin.
And now the dungeon was done, and the party was leaving, and she was standing at the edge of the group trying to find the words for something she had never asked anyone before.
"I've learned more in the last few hours with you than I have in years at the College."
Her voice was quiet. Not the trembling whisper of the girl who had hidden in a storage closet. Something steadier, though still fragile at the edges.
"The Masters here... they watch me. They study me. They want to use what I can do, but none of them want to teach me how to control it. I'm a specimen to them. An anomaly to be catalogued."
She touched the black soul gems around her neck.
"You didn't treat me like that. You let me help. You let me be useful instead of dangerous."
She looked at each of them. Kyboh ΓÇö noncommittal, wary. Saijah ΓÇö sympathetic but uncertain. Orion ΓÇö watching, assessing, giving nothing away. Davinia ΓÇö the only one whose expression held something warmer, recognition perhaps, one woman carrying an unwanted power acknowledging another.
But it was Alfonso who spoke.
"Come with us."
The others looked at him. Alfonso ΓÇö the thing that used to be a vampire, the man who carried two warring divine frequencies in his chest and a crown of dragon bone on his skull, who hadn't figured out what he was becoming and might not live long enough to find out ΓÇö looked at the terrified prodigy and saw something none of the others had articulated.
"You're stronger than anyone in this College," he said. "Stronger than the Masters who are afraid of you. Stronger than the students who whisper about you. You dismantled a Master-level Conjuration in the Arcanaeum without thinking about it. You navigated the Midden like it was your living room. You stood in a room with a Flesh Atronach and didn't run."
He met her eyes directly.
"The Lanterns could use someone like you. And I think you could use people who aren't afraid of what you are."
Nora's hands stopped trembling. Not because the fear was gone ΓÇö it was still there, a constant companion, the terror of her own capabilities that had defined her since she was six years old. But Alfonso's words had landed somewhere beneath the fear, in the place where a young woman's desperate need to belong had been waiting for someone to say yes instead of be careful.
"I... are you sure? I can't always controlΓÇö"
"Neither can I," Alfonso said. And the simplicity of it ΓÇö the honesty of a man who knew exactly what it meant to carry power that might destroy you ΓÇö closed the distance between them.
Nora nodded. Once. Small. But certain.
"Okay. I'm coming with you."
She was an Obsidian Lantern now. The most powerful person in the room, and the most afraid of it. She fit right in.

PART III: THE SINGING SEA
The Drop
They blew the drainage grate with Destruction magic and dropped to the frozen shelf of ice at the base of the College pillar. The wind screamed around them. The Sea of Ghosts crashed against the rocks below, sending up plumes of freezing spray.
Looking north through the blizzard, barely visible, a spire of ice caught the light wrong. It didn't shine. It sang.
The Glacier that Sings. Hjolmar's forge.
But between them and the glacier lay the Singing Sea ΓÇö a field of frictionless ice that stretched across the strait like a frozen mirror. The tonal frequency from the glacier vibrated the sea ice at a molecular level, eliminating all surface friction.
Nothing gripped. Boots slid. Weapons skidded. If you pushed something, it moved until it hit something else. If you pushed off something, you moved until you hit something else.
Newton's laws, enforced by ancient magic, with lethal water on all sides.
The Crossing
They broke a massive slab of sea ice free from the frozen shore ΓÇö forty feet across, flat, thick ΓÇö and stepped onto their raft. The moment their weight hit the surface, they understood the problem. Every step sent them sliding. Every gesture created momentum. The ice was a frictionless plane, and they were objects in motion with no way to stop.
Kyboh solved the propulsion. His Boots of the Comet granted ice immunity ΓÇö the cold couldn't touch him. He jumped off the back of the floe, his body mass propelling the slab forward, then used the boots' velocity to circle back and leap aboard again. He became the engine, kicking off the trailing edge, sprinting across the surface of the lethal sea, and boarding the moving platform in a continuous cycle.
Each obstacle demanded three of them working in concert while the others braced.
The channel ΓÇö a thirty-foot gap of open black water dead ahead. Davinia froze the surface with a blast of ice architecture, Alfonso tilted the leading edge with telekinesis, and together they ramped the floe over the gap before the temporary bridge could crack.
The basalt pillar ΓÇö volcanic rock coated in ice, directly in their path. Orion aimed his war horn at it and played a sustained resonant note. The ice coating cracked in spirals. The basalt beneath split. The fragments rained across the water around them as they glided through the debris field. The first time Orion had used tonal engineering on the physical environment rather than on enchantments.
The calving glacier ΓÇö no warning, a massive section of glacier wall shearing off and crashing into the sea. The wave hit the underside of the floe and tilted it violently. Everyone slid toward one edge. Saijah air-dashed to the person closest to the water and caught them. Kyboh planted himself as a human wall for others to crash into instead of sliding off.
The drift ΓÇö the current pulling them sideways toward the open ocean. Alfonso fired a sustained force spell off one edge to correct their course while Davinia read the tonal field with her new eyes and called out the direction where the resonance was strongest.
The collision ΓÇö another floe, bigger than theirs, moving perpendicular. All five acted. Orion cracked it with his horn. Davinia built a reinforced ice wall on the contact side. Alfonso generated a force barrier. Kyboh braced on the impact edge as a human shock absorber. Saijah positioned herself to grab whoever got knocked loose. The floes scraped together with a grinding sound that shook their teeth, shearing off a strip of their platform.
The fog ΓÇö whiteout conditions, visibility dropping to five feet. But Davinia could see. Her Wizard Sight didn't rely on visible light. She saw the tonal field, the obstacles, the glacier ahead as patterns of energy. She stood at the front and called directions while her blind teammates executed. The Crown hummed with approval ΓÇö making her feel powerful, needed, irreplaceable. Making the new eyes feel like a gift instead of a leash.
